n during emergencies. In making his case, Ackerman explores emergency provisions in constitutions of nations ranging from France to South Africa, retaining aspects that work and adapting others. He shows that no country today is well equipped to both fend off terrorists and preserve fundamental liberties, drawing particular attention to recent British reactions to terrorist attacks. Written for thoughtful citizens throughout the world, this book is democracy's constitutional reply to political excess in the sinister era of terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMesures d'exceptionxÉtats-Unis. 0aOpération Liberté immuable, 2001-xDroitxÉtats-Unis. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aTerrorismxUnited States. 0aTerrorismzUnited States. 0aTerrorismexÉtats-Unis. 0aWar and emergency legislationxUnited States. 0aWar and emergency legislationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300127034.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles